<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-05-23T07:44:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-05-23T07:44:00-05:00" n="707" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d707">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">882.6851 U. S. Steel Corp./68:
                                Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in Liberia</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Walton</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Monrovia</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-05-23T12:00:00-00:44">May 23,
                                    1939—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received May 23—8:11 a.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>33. United States Steel engineers to sail last of May.</p>
                            <p>Their probable return to Liberia gives me reason to surmise that <pb facs="0632" n="626" xml:id="pg_626"/> desirable iron deposits
                                were discovered in Bolahun and other areas. No results of survey
                                will be made known to Liberian Government until United States Steel
                                Corporation receives formal report by same careful study.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Walton</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>